#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:453
#, no-wrap
msgid "Make sure the password is secure and, again, log it somewhere safe, such as a password manager. You'll also need to fill in the email address for the administrative user. Once all of that is completed, simply click the \"Add User\" button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:455
#, no-wrap
msgid "![LibreNMS Administrative User](../images/librenms_administrative_user.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:457
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you do this, you'll be faced with a screen for \"Finish Install.\" There should only be one item left to finish the install and that is a line that asks you to \"validate your install\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:459
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click the link. Once you've done this and everything is successful, you'll be redirected to the login page. Login with your administrative user and password.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:460
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding Devices"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:463
#, no-wrap
msgid "Again, one of our assumptions was that you are using SNMP v2. Remember that each device you add must be member of your community string. We are adding two devices as examples here. An Ubuntu workstation and a CentOS server. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:465
#, no-wrap
msgid "You will more than likely have managed switches, routers, and other devices to add. The author can tell you from past experience that adding switches and routers tends to be a whole lot easier than adding workstations and servers, which is why we are including the more difficult examples.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:466
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ubuntu Workstation Setup"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:469
#, no-wrap
msgid "First, install _snmpd_ on the workstation while also updating packages, just to be safe:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:470
#, no-wrap
msgid "sudo update && sudo apt-get upgrade && sudo apt-get install snmpd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:475
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next, you need to modify the snmpd.conf file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:476
#, no-wrap
msgid "sudo vi /etc/snmpd/snmpd.conf\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:481
#, no-wrap
msgid "Go ahead and find the lines that describe your workstation and change them to things that identify the workstation. These lines are shown below:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:482
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sysLocation    Desktop\n"
"sysContact     Username <user@mydomain.com>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:488
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, when you install snmpd on Ubuntu, it only binds to the local address. It does not listen on your machine IP address. This will not allow LibreNMS to connect to it. We need to remark out this line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:489
#, no-wrap
msgid "agentaddress  127.0.0.1,[::1]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:494
#, no-wrap
msgid "And add a new line that looks like what follows here: (In this example, the IP address of our workstation is 192.168.1.122 and the UDP port we are setting is \"161\")\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:495
#, no-wrap
msgid "agentAddress udp:127.0.0.1:161,udp:192.168.1.122:161\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:500
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next, we need to specify the read only access community string. Find the below lines and remark them out. (Note that we are showing them as remarked out below.)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:501
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#rocommunity public default -V systemonly\n"
"#rocommunity6 public default -V systemonly\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:507
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next, add a new line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:508
#, no-wrap
msgid "rocommunity LABone\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:515
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enable and start _snmpd_:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:516
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sudo systemctl enable snmpd\n"
"sudo systemctl start snmpd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:522
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you are running a firewall on your internal workstations, then you will need to modify the firewall to allow UDP traffic from the monitoring server or from the network. LibreNMS also wants to be able to \"ping\" your device, so make sure that icmp port 8 is allowed from the server.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:523
#, no-wrap
msgid "CentOS or Rocky Linux Server Setup"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:526
#, no-wrap
msgid "We are assuming that you are root here or that you can _sudo_ to become so. First, we need to install some packages:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:527
#, no-wrap
msgid "dnf install net-snmp net-snmp-utils\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:532
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next, we want to create a snmpd.conf file. Rather than try to navigate through the file that is included, move this file to rename it, and create a brand new empty file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:533
#, no-wrap
msgid "mv /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf.orig\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:544
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next copy the below into the new file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:545
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Map 'LABone' community to the 'AllUser'\n"
"# sec.name source community\n"
"com2sec AllUser default LABone\n"
"# Map 'ConfigUser' to 'ConfigGroup' for SNMP Version 2c\n"
"# Map 'AllUser' to 'AllGroup' for SNMP Version 2c\n"
"# sec.model sec.name\n"
"group AllGroup v2c AllUser\n"
"# Define 'SystemView', which includes everything under .1.3.6.1.2.1.1 (or .1.3.6.1.2.1.25.1)\n"
"# Define 'AllView', which includes everything under .1\n"
"# incl/excl subtree\n"
"view SystemView included .1.3.6.1.2.1.1\n"
"view SystemView included .1.3.6.1.2.1.25.1.1\n"
"view AllView included .1\n"
"# Give 'ConfigGroup' read access to objects in the view 'SystemView'\n"
"# Give 'AllGroup' read access to objects in the view 'AllView'\n"
"# context model level prefix read write notify\n"
"access AllGroup \"\" any noauth exact AllView none none\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:566
#, no-wrap
msgid "CentOS and Rocky use a mapping convention to direct things. The above file is commented nicely so that you can learn what is happening, but doesn't include all of the clutter of the original file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:568
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you've made the changes, save them and exit the file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:570
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now we need to enable and start _snmpd_:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:571
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"systemctl enable snmpd\n"
"systemctl start snmpd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:576
#, no-wrap
msgid "Firewall"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:579
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you are running a server, then you **are** running a firewall, right?  If you are running _firewalld_ (as you should be) we will assume that we are using the \"trusted\" zone here and we just want to allow all traffic from our monitoring server, 192.168.1.140:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:580
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --add-source=192.168.1.140 --permanent\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:585
#, no-wrap
msgid "Again, we assumed the \"trusted\" zone here, but you may want something else, even \"public\", just consder your rules and their affects before adding them in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:586
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding The Devices In Librenms"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:589
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now that our sample devices are configured to accept snmp traffic from our LibreNMS server, the next step is to add those devices in LibreNMS. We are assuming that you have the web interface for LibreNMS open, and if so, it is going to be showing you that you have no devices added and asking you to add one. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:591
#, no-wrap
msgid "So go ahead and do that. Once you click to add a device, you'll be faced with this screen:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:593
#, no-wrap
msgid "![LibreNMS Add Device](../images/librenms_add_device.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:595
#, no-wrap
msgid "Put in the information we used for our test devices. In our case, we are using the IP for the Ubuntu workstation to start, in our example that is 192.168.1.122. The only other thing we will need to add here is the community string in the \"Community\" field, so we would type in \"LABone\" here. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:597
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now click the \"Add Device\" button. Assuming that you have done everything correctly above when adding the device, your device should be added successfully. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:599
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you run into a \"failure to add\" error, review the SNMP setup for the workstation or the firewall if it exists. Next we repeat the \"Add Device\" process for our CentOS server.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:600
#, no-wrap
msgid "Getting Alerts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:603
#, no-wrap
msgid "As we said from the start, this document will only get you started with LibreNMS. There are a large number of additional configuration items, an extensive API (Application Programming Interface), an alerts system that provides a huge number of options for delivery, called \"Transports\", and much more. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:605
#, no-wrap
msgid "We are not going to create any alert rules, but instead we will be editing the built-in alert rule \"Device Down! Due to no ICMP response\"  that is pre-configured out of the box, and for \"Transports\" we are going to stick with \"Mail\", which is just email. Just know that you are not limited.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:607
#, no-wrap
msgid "In order to use email for our transport, however, we need to have mail working on our server. To get this going, we are going to use this [Postfix Procedure](../email/postfix_reporting.md). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:609
#, no-wrap
msgid "Run through that procedure to configure postfix so that it will properly identify where the messages are coming from, but you can stop after the configuration process and come back here.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:610
#, no-wrap
msgid "Transports"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:613
#, no-wrap
msgid "We need a way to send out our alerts. As noted earlier, LibreNMS supports a huge number of transports. We are going to do our alert by email, which is defined as the \"Mail\" transport. To set up the transport:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:622
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:637
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:650
#, no-wrap
msgid "Go to the dashboard\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:622
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:650
#, no-wrap
msgid "Let your mouse hover over \"Alerts\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:622
#, no-wrap
msgid "Go down to \"Alert Transports\" and click on it\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:622
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click on on the \"Create alert transport\" button (Note the \"Create transport group\" button. You can use this to have alerts go to several individuals)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:622
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the \"Transport name:\" field, type in \"Alert By Email\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '6. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:622
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the \"Transport type: field, use the drop down to select \"Mail\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '7. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:622
#, no-wrap
msgid "Make sure the \"Default alert:\" field is set to \"On\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '8. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:622
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the \"Email:\" field, type the email address of the administrator\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:623
#, no-wrap
msgid "Organizing Devices Into Groups"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:626
#, no-wrap
msgid "The best way to set up alerts is to first organize your devices into some logical order. Currently, we have a workstation and a server in devices. While we may not normally wish combine the two, we will for this example.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:628
#, no-wrap
msgid "Keep in mind that our example is also redundant, as there is an \"All Devices\" group that would work for this as well. To set up a device group:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:637
#, no-wrap
msgid "Let your mouse hover over \"Devices\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:637
#, no-wrap
msgid "Go down to \"Manage Groups\" and click on it\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:637
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the \"+ New Device Group\" button\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:637
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the \"Name\" field, type \"ICMP Group\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '6. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:637
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the description field type what ever you think will help describe the group\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '7. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:637
#, no-wrap
msgid "Change the \"Type\" field from \"Dynamic\" to \"Static\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '8. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:637
#, no-wrap
msgid "Add both devices to the \"Select Devices\" field and then just save your changes\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:638
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting Up The Alert Rules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/network/librenms_monitoring_server.md:641
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now that we have the transport and the device group set up, let's configure the alert rule. By default, LibreNMS has several alert rules already created for you:\n"
